Bar

library(dplyr)
gg2 <- filter(txhousing, year> 2014)
gg3 <- select(gg2, city:sales)
gg4 <- ggplot(gg3)
gg4 + geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = month, fill = city))+ labs(x = "Month", y = "relative frequencies")

## Using google map to show the population of Texas

library(maps)
data("us.cities")
library(ggmap)
## Google's Terms of Service: https://cloud.google.com/maps-platform/terms/.
## Please cite ggmap if you use it! See citation("ggmap") for details.
register_google(key = "AIzaSyAei_JxAaCgQPPdUZeQU4cy398_08MtFiQ")
tx_center = as.numeric(geocode("Texas"))
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/geocode/json?address=Texas&key=xxx
txMap = ggmap(get_googlemap(center=tx_center, scale=2, zoom=6), extent="normal")
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=31.968599,-99.901813&zoom=6&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&key=xxx
tx.cities <-subset(us.cities, country.etc == "TX")
txMap + geom_point(aes(x=long, y=lat, size=pop), col = "blue", data = tx.cities, alpha = 0.5)+ggtitle("pupulation of texas cities")
